<HEADLINE>
FT  16 AUG 94 / London to list global depositary receipts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The London Stock Exchange yesterday announced that it is establishing its
first global depositary receipts programme enabling foreign companies to
obtain a full London share listing.
The move to allow global depositary receipts - sterling-denominated bundles
of shares - is part of the exchange's effort to market itself to non-UK
companies and strengthen its position in international share trading.
Mr Michael Lawrence, exchange chief executive, has pointed to the success of
US exchanges in attracting foreign companies, particularly those based in
emerging markets. This has strengthened the international role of the US
exchanges.
Mr David Landman, executive director at Morgan Stanley, the US-based
investment bank, said that London's pre-eminent position as a global
financial centre would be strengthened as a result of the introduction of
depository receipts.
The exchange expects the strongest interest in obtaining a listing for
depositary receipts to come from companies based in emerging markets.
Yesterday the Inland Revenue said that unlike trading in the shares of UK
listed companies, depositary receipts would not attract the standard 0.5 per
cent stamp duty on each transaction. Issuers would, however, have to pay
stamp duty of 1.5 per cent on all shares transferred into the depositary
receipts programme.
The rules are intended to make trading in depositary receipts competitive
with trading costs in the home country. Listing requirements and fees for
those seeking global depositary receipt status will be lower than for an
outright London listing, although the requirements may be no weaker than the
minimum set out in European Union legislation.
The issuer must have a three-year trading record and although audited
accounts for the previous three years must be presented, the accounts need
not be prepared in accordance with international accounting standards, nor
need they be consolidated.
The depositary, typically a bank, must be one which is acceptable to the
exchange and there must be at least one firm which agrees to act as market
maker.
Continuing obligations will include a requirement to notify the exchange in
the event of a price-sensitive development. Annual and half-yearly reports
must be released within six months of the period to which they relate. The
initial listing fee will be Pounds 4,000 and the annual fee Pounds 2,000.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6231 Security and Commodity Exchanges.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
