group it was willing to lift its bid from Dollars 95 a share to Dollars 100
if the group's board agreed to the offer by tonight. The new offer values
Cyanamid at more than Dollars 9bn.
AHP, however, warned that it would pursue its original bid if an agreed deal
could not be negotiated.
There was no immediate response from Cyanamid, which last week urged its
shareholders not to accept the unsolicited bid until its board had fully
reviewed the bid. If the new offer is rejected, the stage will be set for a
proxy battle for control of Cyana-mid.
Yesterday's developments came a day after Mr Jack Stafford, chairman of AHP
(whose interests range from prescription drugs to confectionery), met his
counterpart at Cyanamid, Mr Albert Costello.
At that meeting, Mr Stafford failed to persuade Mr Costello to accept AHP's
offer, and in a letter to the Cyanamid chief yesterday he expressed his
disappointment at their lack of agreement. Mr Stafford wrote: 'While we have
always believed that our Dollars 95 per share offer represented a full and
fair price, as I stated last night, we were willing to propose an increase
of that price to Dollars 100 on the basis of our belief that such an
increase would permit us to reach agreement and proceed rapidly to conclude
a transaction supported by both companies.'
Although Cyanamid's management is thought to oppose a takeover by AHP,
analysts believe it will be difficult for the board to reject an offer which
values the group's shares at a more than 50 per cent premium over their
pre-bid price.
If Home Products wins control of Cyanamid, it will be the largest takeover
yet in the spate of deals currently reshaping the US drugs industry.
</TEXT>
