<HEADLINE>
FT  16 AUG 94 / London Stock Exchange: Dealing profits hit HSBC
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEVE THOMPSON, CHRISTOPHER PRICE, JOEL KIBAZO and SAQIB QURESHI
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The sharp fall in dealing profits at international banking group HSBC
Holdings took the market by surprise, sending the shares tumbling, after it
reported favourable interim figures.
Headline profits up 24 per cent at Pounds 1.46bn were better than
anticipated, but it was the fall in profits from treasury and capital market
operations at subsidiaries Midland Bank and HongKong Bank that raised most
concern. Analysts were also disappointed by the big rise in the tax charge.
The shares fell back sharply and were down 20 at the day's worst before
recovering to end 10 off at 749p, as sentiment shifted its focus to the
lower than expected bad debt provisions. Volume stood at 6.9m shares at the
close.
Several brokers said that they would be upgrading full-year profit
expectations. That list includes Mr Simon Samuels at Smith New Court who
indicated that his current forecast of Pounds 2.8bn will be raised to around
Pounds 3.1bn.
However, he remains cautious on the stock and said: 'The concerns raised by
the poor quality of earnings in 1993 was further highlighted by these
figures. I feel the shares are fully priced at these levels. Hong Kong
investors will be concerned about the significantly higher tax charge.'
</TEXT>
