<HEADLINE>
FT  16 AUG 94 / International Capital Markets: Hang Seng Bank interim
results below expectations
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE LUCAS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   HONG KONG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Hang Seng Bank, the Hong Kong subsidiary of the Hongkong and Shanghai
Banking Corporation, lifted net profits by 13.2 per cent to HKDollars 3.1bn
(USDollars 401m) for the first half of 1994 from HKDollars 2.7bn in the same
period last year, but the result was below expectations.
Operating profits were squeezed by the narrowing of the spread between the
best lending rate and the savings deposit rate; the elimination of exchange
gains on Hong Kong dollar notes (following the change of the settlement
currency to Hong Kong dollars in January); and the reversal in the latter
half of last year of an over-provision relating to the accrued liabilities
of the staff retirement benefit schemes.
Sir Quo-Wei Lee, chairman, said: 'Competition for deposits remained intense,
in particular Hong Kong dollar wholesale deposits, and the interest margin
was under pressure. In such an operating environment, Hang Seng's result for
the first half of 1994 was satisfactory.'
The market had been looking for growth in excess of 15 per cent, but
disappointment in results from the banking sector had already been signalled
by Bank of East Asia, Hong Kong's third biggest listed bank, which last
month reported a 12 per cent improvement at the interim stage.
Standard Chartered, the UK-based international bank which is one of Hong
Kong's three note issuing banks, added to the gloom in the colony's banking
sector last week when it reported a drop in profits from Hong Kong, to
Pounds 108m (USDollars 167.40m) from Pounds 122m.
Hang Seng said government measures to cool property prices, announced in
June but signalled in March, had already fed through to a slowdown in
mortgage lending.
The bank is paying an interim dividend of HKDollars 0.60, up 20 per cent on
the HKDollars 0.50 paid out last year at the interim stage.
However, directors were quick to warn that this should not be construed as
an indication of the profit trend in the second half, but rather as a
symptom of Hang Seng's strong capital base, reflected in its 27.8 per cent
risk asset ratio. Earnings per share stand at HKDollars 1.61, up from
HKDollars 1.42 in the first half of 1993.
Provisions for bad and doubtful debts were slashed to HKDollars 43.8m,
compared with HKDollars 72.3m in the same period last year.
