<PROFILE>_AN-EHPE7AFDFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940816
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  16 AUG 94 / Government Bonds: Treasuries soften ahead of Fed meeting
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANK MCGURTY and ANTONIA SHARPE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
US Treasury bond prices softened in light trading yesterday as the market
braced itself for a move by the Federal Reserve to raise short-term interest
rates.
Late in the session, the benchmark 30-year government bond was  3/32 lower
at 99 13/32 , with the yield rising to 7.504 per cent. At the short end, the
two-year note was down  1/32 at 99 3/4 , to yield 6.244 per cent.
With the Fed set to convene its policy-making session today, traders were
convinced a rate increase was inevitable.
Last week's data on inflation and retail sales, coupled with the continued
strength of the employment market, provided ample evidence for the central
bank to tighten credit conditions for the fifth time this year, according to
most analysts. Yesterday's economic news did nothing to undermine that view.
The Fed announced a 0.2 per cent increase in industrial production last
month, while capacity utilisation - an important barometer of incipient
price pressures - held steady at 83.9 per cent.
While the July figures represented a slowdown, the data were still well
above a level which would suggest the economy had shifted into low gear.
Still, the reaction was muted, as a rate increase appeared to be already
priced into Treasury bonds. Prices dipped on the news, edged back just
before mid-day and receded again during the late afternoon.
The only outstanding question was whether the bank would lift the Federal
Funds rate by 25 or 50 basis points.
A more aggressive move could prove to be a positive development for the
inflation-sensitive long end of the maturity range.
Analysts said a 50-point increase would demonstrate the central bank's
vigilance against inflation. In addition, it would not leave the market
wondering if yet another small rate increase was just around the corner.
Still, most analysts were expecting the Fed to strike the more cautious
course. 'There is still too much uncertainty regarding the economy's
performance for the Fed to firm by more than 25 points,' said Mr Elliot
Platt of Donaldson, Lufkin &amp; Jenrette, the New York securities house.
The public holiday in many parts of Europe crippled trading in the
government bond markets which were open for business yesterday.
However, dealers are preparing themselves for a sudden increase in activity
in the event of the Federal Reserve raising interest rates today.
'This is an important week for bond markets despite the deceptively quiet
atmosphere,' said Ms Wendy Niffikeer of IBJ International.
The market is also waiting for guidance from the Bundesbank, which is due to
resume its fortnightly council meetings on Thursday after the four-week
summer break. The scheduled run of four fixed-rate repos, set at 4.85 per
cent, comes to an end this week.
Ms Niffikeer said the market's attention had shifted away from a rate cut in
Germany, following last week's rises in Italy and Sweden.
Nevertheless, she believed a decision to keep the repo fixed at 4.85 per
cent would be damaging to an already fragile market. 'Any cut in the repo
would be favourable,' she said.
The market is clearly divided about the Bundesbank's intentions. Ms Alison
Cottrell, international economist at Midland Global Markets, believes the
gap of 35 basis points between the repo and the discount rates, although
wide in theory, may be too tight to allow the Bundesbank to return to its
preferred variable repo rate.
'In the absence of an official rate cut, do not expect the repo rate to look
too dissimilar to 4.85 per cent - whether fixed or variable,' she advises.
Mr Holger Fahrinkrug of UBS in Frankfurt says a return to variable repos
should be seen as confirmation that the Bundesbank sees scope for a further
discount rate cut.
Activity in both cash and futures markets was quiet yesterday. On Liffe, the
September bund future was virtually unchanged at 91.57 with 56,338 contracts
traded. The September long gilt future rose  1/16 to 100 3/4 .
The Bank of England said two tranches of index-linked bonds totalling Pounds
200m were exhausted yesterday. Dealers estimated that as much as 90 per cent
of the Pounds 500m of outstanding taps was still unsold.
</TEXT>
