<HEADLINE>
FT  16 AUG 94 / UK Company News: Huntingdon shares shed 9p after third
quarter decline
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JEAN MARSHALL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Shares in Huntingdon International Holdings fell 9p to close at 65p after
the life sciences group announced a drop in pre-tax profits from Pounds
10.1m to Pounds 3.34m in the nine months to end-June. Revenue, net of
subcontracts, fell from Pounds 115.6m to Pounds 109.2m.
For the three months to June 30, the fall was from Pounds 4.32m to Pounds
774,000 on revenues of Pounds 35.7m (Pounds 38.7m).
Mr Ian Campbell, chairman, said the nine-month results were disappointing.
Although current trading was stronger in all operating groups, he said it
was unlikely there would be an overall improvement in the fourth quarter.
In May, the group said it would concentrate on its life sciences business
and Mr Campbell said yesterday that discussions were under way with
potential purchasers for both its US engineering and environmental services
business and for Travers Morgan, its UK-based consultancy.
For the nine months there were losses of Pounds 299,000 (Pounds 2.77m
profits) from US engineering while Travers Morgan contributed just Pounds
183,000 (Pounds 1.89m).
Life sciences slipped to Pounds 5.83m (Pounds 6.6m) as a result of price
competition, lower-than-anticipated throughput and increased unit costs.
However, the installation of new equipment had been speeded up at Huntingdon
Research Centre and additional staff recruited. Also, both forward orders
and quotations were now 13 per cent ahead of last year with orders from
Japan and the US considerably higher.
Mr Campbell added that having initiated a 'comprehensive restructuring' of
the group, he intended to step down once a replacement had been found.
</TEXT>
