<HEADLINE>
FT  16 AUG 94 / HSBC stops own-account bond trading: Pre-tax profits up 24
per cent at Pounds 1.46bn - Sharp drop in dealing income
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER, Banking Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HSBC Holdings, the international banking group, has largely suspended
proprietary trading on bond markets after losing Pounds 123m on bond and
interest rate-related trading during a turbulent first half, it disclosed
yesterday.
HSBC's shares fell 10p to 749p after it revealed that its exposure to
financial trading led to a 10 per cent fall in non-interest income to Pounds
1.47bn. This included a sharp drop in dealing income to Pounds 73m from
Pounds 522m.
Despite the setback, a fall in provisions for bad and doubtful debts to
Pounds 173m from Pounds 432m allowed HSBC to raise pre-tax profits by 24 per
cent to Pounds 1.46bn from Pounds 1.18bn. The interim dividend goes up 14
per cent to 8p.
Sir William Purves, HSBC chairman, said that the bank's treasury had been
positioned for a rise in US interest rates in February, but was caught out
by the 'rather drastic' rise in European bond yields that accompanied this.
None of HSBC's internal limits were breached and no staff had been
dismissed. But HSBC was 'not running significant positions today and we will
not start again until we see markets that are more predictable'.
Dealing income from foreign exchange rose to Pounds 196m from Pounds 180m.
But it lost Pounds 92m on proprietory position taking in interest rate
products, and lost a further Pounds 31m on other, primarily interest
rate-related, trading.
Losses continued at Concord Leasing, its US leasing arm, which has suffered
from falls in the value of commercial aircraft. It lost Pounds 100m, against
Pounds 22m in the first half of 1993 and Pounds 140m in the second half.
Sir William said HSBC had changed Concord's chief executive and was
negotiating with US banking regulators to fold it into Marine Midland, its
US banking subsidiary. This would help it to use tax allowances arising from
the losses.
There was strong asset growth in Hong Kong, with advances at its subsidiary
HongkongBank rising by 5.7 per cent from the end of 1993. This was due to
demand for residential mortgages and corporate loans, and buoyant trade
finance.
The net interest margin stayed at 2.7 per cent, with interest-earning assets
rising to Pounds 169bn from Pounds 159bn. Margins in HongkongBank narrowed
from 2.4 to 2.3 per cent, mainly because of narrowing spreads on
liabilities.
Sir William said that he had 'no gleam in my eye' over the possibility of
acquiring a UK building society. A purchase to add to Marine Midland was
more likely, but it was unwilling to pay current prices for US regional
banks.
The annualised post-tax return on equity fell slightly to 19.3 per and the
return on assets stayed at 1 per cent. The tier 1 ratio of capital to
risk-weighted assets rose from 7.5 to 8.6 per cent.
Profit attributable to shareholders advanced 13 per cent to Pounds 938m. The
increase was lower than the rise in pre-tax profits because tax allowances
from past losses have been used at Midland, and largely used at Marine
Midland.
Lex, Page 16; Midland, Page 19; Hang Seng Bank, Page 23
