<HEADLINE>
FT  16 AUG 94 / Life on the edge as Confed collapse shakes up insurers:
Bernard Simon sees nervousness in a Canadian industry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A shiver has rippled through Canada's life insurance industry after last
week's collapse of Confederation Life, the fourth biggest domestic insurer.
Since regulators decided to take over Confederation last Thursday, pending
the winding-up and liquidation of the Toronto-based company, other companies
have rushed to reassure employees and policyholders that Confed is a special
case and that its problems are not typical of the industry.
Confed's businesses were relatively sound, but it was dragged down by a
1980s foray into property development and lending, with property making up
more than 60 per cent of its investments.
The concern remains, however, that the biggest failure of a life insurer in
North America, involving a company with CDollars 19bn (Pounds 8.9bn) in
balance sheet assets and CDollars 33bn in assets under management, could set
off a chain of events.
Canada's life insurance industry has for long enjoyed a solid reputation.
The biggest companies, Manulife Financial (formerly Manufacturers Life), Sun
Life of Canada and Canada Life, are strongly capitalised and have blue-chip
credit ratings. The biggest companies are also diversified. More than
two-thirds of Sun Life's assets under management are in the US. Manulife is
the third biggest life underwriter in Hong Kong, and writes more business in
Asia than in Canada.
But pressures on the industry have been building. About 150 life companies
compete in a stagnant market. Underwriting margins have narrowed so that
many companies rely on investment income and diversification - into mutual
funds, for instance - to keep them in the black.
Standard &amp; Poor's said this month that while the nine biggest companies
'continue offering a high level of financial security', it expects to
downgrade some credit ratings over the next few years.
Although Confed was heavily exposed to property, the slump in North American
property values has hit the entire industry. Even Sun Life suffered
investment losses, mainly from its property portfolio, of CDollars 255m last
year - a 66 per cent jump from 1992.
The diminishing rewards of the Canadian insurance market are apparent in a
spate of deals. New York Life earlier this year ended a 136-year presence in
Canada by selling its operations to Canada Life. Sun Alliance sold its
Canadian unit to North American Life at the end of May.
More recently, the UK's Prudential group has sold its Canadian group life
and health business, as well as its group pension-plan operations, to Sun
Life. Several other foreign companies are rumoured to be struggling to find
buyers. Regulatory curbs, such as a 25 per cent limit on foreign
shareholdings, have also discouraged mergers and takeovers.
Mr Mark Daniels, president of the Canadian Life and Health Insurance
Association, says the Confed failure could speed rationalisation and
predicts 'significantly fewer players' over the next five to 10 years.
Confed's collapse may encourage Canada's six big banks to accelerate their
drive into insurance, he adds. Several have bought insurance operations
since the lifting of restrictions in mid-1992, but have yet to make an
impact on the market.
Meanwhile the industry is braced for a 'flight to quality'. Companies seen
to be vulnerable could find it difficult to sell policies or attract savings
and there is concern that some may have difficulty raising funds.
Insurers also face a costly call for contributions to CompCorp, the
industry's consumer-protection fund of which membership is compulsory.
Unlike most deposit-insurance schemes, members are assessed for funds only
after a member has been declared insolvent. The industry coughed up CDollars
180m in 1992-93 to pay policyholders of Les Cooperants, a Montreal-based
company. Another CDollars 75m or so will be required to meet the obligations
of Sovereign Life of Calgary, which failed in late 1992. These sums are
likely to pale against CompCorp's obligations to Confed policyholders.
What is especially galling to insurers is that depositors in the rash of
Canadian trust companies which have failed have been compensated by the
government, through the Canada Deposit Insurance Corporation. Insurers now
face a period of similar turmoil. But while taxpayers footed much of the
trust industry's bill, insurers themselves will have to carry the burden for
those who fall by the wayside. That prospect may provide a powerful
incentive for stepping up the pace of mergers and acquisitions before more
companies go the way of Confederation Life.
Lex, Page 16; Credit ratings, Page 23
</TEXT>
<XX>
