<HEADLINE>
FT  16 AUG 94 / London Stock Exchange woos listings by foreign companies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The London Stock Exchange is to set up its first-ever share listing
programme for foreign companies who want to tap into the UK's capital
market.
The move, announced yesterday, is part of the exchange's efforts to market
itself to non-UK companies, strengthening its role as a centre for
international share trading.
Mr Michael Lawrence, London Stock Exchange chief executive, has pointed to
the success of US exchanges in attracting foreign companies, particularly
those based in emerging markets, to seek listings there.
The success of the New York stock exchange and the Nasdaq stock market in
attracting these companies has strengthened the role of the US exchanges in
international share trading. Under the programme, foreign companies will be
invited to set up so-called depositary receipts. These are
sterling-denominated bundles of shares in a single company held by a trust
bank which then issues certificates. The number of shares per bundle and the
underlying currency will vary with each issuing company.
The exchange expects the strongest interest in obtaining a listing for
depositary receipts to come from companies based in emerging markets such as
South East Asia and Latin America.
Yesterday, the Inland Revenue said that unlike trading in the shares of
UK-listed companies, investors would not pay the standard 0.5 per cent stamp
duty on each depositary receipt transaction. However, issuing companies will
have to pay stamp duty of 1.5 per cent on all shares transformed into
depositary receipts.
The rules are intended to make trading in the depositary receipts
competitive with trading costs in the home country.
Listing requirements and fees for those seeking depositary receipt status
will be lower than for UK companies on the Official List. However, they will
conform to the minimum set out in European Union law. The issuer must have a
three-year trading record and, although audited accounts for the previous
three years must be presented, the accounts may be prepared in accordance
with home country standards. They also need not be consolidated.
The depositary, typically a bank, must be acceptable to the exchange, and
there must be at least one firm which agrees to act as market maker in
respect of each company's depositary receipts.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
