<HEADLINE>
FT  16 AUG 94 / Observer: Idaho . . .the pot state
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Northwest Airlines is flying high. Or at least one of its co-chairmen has
been. Returning from a rafting holiday in Idaho, Gary Wilson was passing
through the security screening point at Boise airport when he was
apprehended by security officials puzzled by an X-ray image of an
oddly-shaped object in his bag.
On close examination, the object turned out to be a kind of pipe, and with
it were 2.7 grams of marijuana. The red-faced Wilson was fined Dollars 500
and, on reporting back to Northwest Airlines' head office in St Paul,
Minnesota, suspended himself from duty pending an internal inquiry.
In all probability, he will soon be back at his desk. After all, he is more
of an investor than an executive; with Alfred Checchi, the other
co-chairman, he led a Dollars 3.6bn buy-out of Northwest in 1989 which took
the airline private. Also, he was off duty at the time, and the airline says
that other employees committing comparable misdemeanours have stayed.
Even so, the turn of events has astonished Northwest's staff. Wilson is 54,
so hardly falls into the category of the Woodstock generation. 'He's the
last person you would suspect. He's such a button-down, senior type of
person,' said one employee. 'It just goes to show; you never can tell . . .'
Come to think of it, has anyone inspected Sir Colin Marshall's hand-baggage
recently?
</TEXT>
