FT  16 AUG 94 / Letters to the Editor: Trying to achieve linguistic purity
can be a laughing matter
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From M S CHANDRAMOULI
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, The brouhaha about the Loi Toubon ('The French choose their words
carefully', August 6) reminds me of the time that Hindi zealots in my native
India ran amuck.
Notably, public institutions were enjoined to have someone write up, on a
daily basis, a 'word for the day' on strip-boards put up at various points
in the building. The 'telephone' became (in translation) a 'distant talker'.
And further shenanigans to this effect. The positive side of the whole
affair was that more people than usual started smiling, and linguistic
'purity' started dissolving in guffaws while people went about the ordinary
business of communicating with each other according to their natural
compulsions.
If the French politician is not careful, he might succeed in prompting the
comment that while the French are a great people, the only problem is they
speak a language called French]
M S Chandramouli,
Quai de la Derivation,
4020 Liege,
Belgium
