FT  16 AUG 94 / Letters to the Editor: Consultants net savings
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr J BLANCHARD SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, I must agree with the title if not with the content of 'Surprising
claim about market testing in efficiency study' (Letters: August 9). The
fact remains that value for money has been achieved with the use of external
consultants. The taxpayer has seen a net saving on a range of projects
through the use of outside consultants.
Furthermore, many agencies compete and succeed in attracting private sector
work through increased efficiency as a result of the implementation of
consultants' recommendations. There will be consultants who do not achieve
the quality or results required and they will not be used again - an option
not available with permanent departments.
An undertaking of the stature of the Market Testing Initiative should be
judged objectively and as a whole, and not, as seems to be the fashion these
days, be subject to sound bites taken out of context.
Should a sound-bite be required, however, the following, drawn from the
Efficiency Unit scrutiny report, may be useful: 'Our scrutiny has left us in
no doubt that consultants have, and will continue to have, significant
'added value' to contribute to departments and agencies.'
Jonathan Blanchard Smith,
publisher,
Wickham House,
Executive Agencies Quarterly,
London E1 4TR
