<HEADLINE>
FT  16 AUG 94 / Letters to the Editor: Military interests don't belong in
politics
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr IAN CAMPBELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, Readers concerned about developments in West Africa will welcome the
balanced approach and relevant conclusions of your editorial, 'Time to help
Nigeria' (August 3).
As you pointed out, it is for Nigerians, soldiers and civilians, to resolve
the present crisis. This does not exclude appropriate measures by British
and other governments to ensure a speedy end to military rule and
installation of a civilian coalition under Chief Moshood Abiola as
president. He was the victor of the presidential election, organised on June
12 1993 by the military regime.
His alleged 'treason', resulting in arrest and trial, derives from the fact
that he won the contest, against the preferred candidate of the military
leadership, while his Yoruba affiliations aroused misgivings in parts of the
north. He won a clear majority in Kano State, home to the opposition
candidate and also to General Sani Abacha, current head of state.
After a year that has seen the military reject the election results, then
'withdraw' only to resume power shortly afterwards, Abiola has recently
asserted his right to assume the presidency under the military-approved
constitution.
At the time of the election his support bridged the religious and ethnic
divisions within the country. His insistence on a negotiated outcome and his
rejection of violence has kept open the possibility of peaceful compromise.
I have recently returned from South Africa and your comparison with the
successful transition in that country is apposite.
The military will best serve its own interests and those of Nigeria by
distancing itself from politics, as in 1979, and giving loyal support to an
incoming civilian regime, restoring the freely elected legislatures, state
and national, as well as the elected state governors. The new regime would
be transitional only in the sense that, after a suitable interval, two or
three years, new elections should be held but no longer restricted to only
two parties.
Ian Campbell,
senior lecturer,
University of Warwick,
Coventry CV4 7AL
</TEXT>
