FT  16 AUG 94 / Letters to the Editor: Many 'food miles' apart
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr HUGH RAVEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, You report (Management: 'Granting an end to the Food Trade Gap', August
11) 'a breakthrough for the UK's vegetable industry' in the form of lettuces
and celery from Cambridgeshire being exported to Belgium. In April, you
reported on a 50-fold increase in the past 10 years of imports of lettuces
from Spain.
The absurdity of this reflects the perversity of the UK's response to its
trade gap in food and drink - a rising proportion of which is accounted for
by foods which could be produced domestically. The Ministry of Agriculture
and its agency Food From Britain have said the gap should be closed via
export promotion rather than import substitution. One of the many
consequences has been an increase in the distances food is transported.
According to Department of Transport, in the 15 years to 1990 more than a
third of the increase in demand for freight was accounted for by food, drink
and tobacco - which account for well under a sixth of the UK economy.
Those who worry about air pollution, congestion and new roads should ponder
these increasing 'food miles' when deciding what to buy on their next trip
to the supermarket.
Hugh Raven,
SAFE Alliance, 38 Ebury Street,
London SW1 0LU
</TEXT>
