<HEADLINE>
FT  16 AUG 94 / Nuclear graveyard claims denied
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Ministry of Defence yesterday denied Labour claims that it plans to turn
the Rosyth naval dockyard into a 'graveyard' for decommissioned
nuclear-powered submarines.
Mr Gordon Brown, the shadow chancellor, said that leaked government
documents showed that seven obsolete nuclear submarines were to be dumped at
the yard.
Mr Brown, whose Dunfermline East constituency includes Rosyth, said that
safety regulations were to be relaxed, leaving the area without proper
protection.
He said that plans to move the navy office responsible for nuclear safety to
Faslane, on the Clyde, and to base tugs used for moving submarines at
Devonport were 'completely unacceptable'.
He added: 'We will not allow the Rosyth area to be frozen by nuclear dumping
or becoming a nuclear graveyard. The government proposals cannot be allowed
to go ahead.'
The MoD said that no decision had been made to lay up nuclear powered
submarines at Rosyth, and denied that the relocation of the navy office
would affect safety.
It added: 'Laid-up nuclear-powered submarines present no hazard to the
general public or the dockyard workforce. There is thus absolutely no reason
why they should have any bearing at all on redevelopment possibilities at
Rosyth.'
There was no difficulty associated with the stationing of tugs at Devonport
because movements of nuclear submarines at Rosyth would be very infrequent
and planned well in advance.
Seven nuclear-powered boats are laid up, four at Rosyth and three at
Devonport. A further four are expected to be decommissioned by the end of
the century.
The radioactive spent fuel and nuclear cores are removed from decommissioned
boats and the hulls are sealed while the level of radioactivity in the
reactor compartments declines.
The Rosyth naval base, which is next to the dockyard, was downgraded to a
support establishment under cost-cutting plans announced last month by Mr
Malcolm Rifkind, defence secretary.
The cuts will have a substantial impact on the local economy. The civilian
workforce will fall from 1,300 to 600 and the number of service personnel
will be cut from 1,800 to 300.
</TEXT>
