<HEADLINE>
FT  16 AUG 94 / Temps hired to tackle insolvency backlog
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government's Insolvency Service was criticised by a trade union
yesterday for hiring temporary staff from recruitment agencies in an effort
to clear a backlog of outstanding regulatory work.
The service has been bringing in extra staff to process thousands of reports
from private-sector insolvency practitioners recommending the
disqualification of directors of failed companies.
The service, which is an executive agency of the Department of Trade and
Industry under the government's Next Steps programme, has been allocated
more than Pounds 1m for the next few months to reduce the backlog of reports
but has avoided hiring full-time staff.
It received only a limited response to its attempt to take on practitioners
seconded from the private sector, and has now turned to two high street
accountancy recruitment agencies to fill the vacancies.
Mr Keith Ellis, chairman of the insolvency service branch of the Institute
of Professional and Managerial Staffs, the civil-service union, said the
policy would be expensive and raised fears about the quality of those hired.
The attempt to boost the number of disqualifications came in response to
publication last year of a highly critical report on the subject from the
National Audit Office, the Whitehall watchdog.
Mr Ellis said: 'If the government was serious about disqualifying directors
it would ensure there were adequate staff to investigate cases fully in the
longer term. This is knee-jerk reaction to the NAO report. They are hoping
it will blow away.'
It also emerged yesterday that the former deputy inspector-general of the
service is considering setting up an advisory service for insolvency
practitioners to help them prepare for visits from regulators.
Mr Philip Pink, a certified accountant and insolvency practitioner, has sent
a circular to individuals and firms offering to review their methods and
compliance standards and to help prepare them for inspections.
The Joint Insolvency Monitoring Unit has recently been set up as part of a
new self-regulatory mechanism under pressure from the DTI to examine
insolvency practitioners. The DTI is inspecting some practitioners directly.
Mr Pink, who left the insolvency service five years ago, has recently been
rehired on an 18-month secondment from Touche Ross.
</TEXT>
