<HEADLINE>
FT  16 AUG 94 / Post office queues to get piped TV shows
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Marketing Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Customers queueing in the 500 largest high street post offices will in
future be able to watch advertising-based television programmes while they
wait, the Post Office has announced.
Programmes will contain film reviews, children's cartoons and competitions,
as well as product information and advertisements. Customers will be able to
pick up leaflets and order forms for goods and services advertised.
Some post offices already show TV advertisements to customers, but this is
the first time full programmes will be shown. The Post Office is one of the
first retailers to experiment with the medium, and
has attracted advertising from Barclaycard, Citroen and Alliance &amp;
Leicester.
Aspen Specialist Media, which will operate the channel, said advertisers
typically paid about Pounds 20,000 for a 30-second commercial which played
up to eight times an hour for five weeks.
Aspen said about 7m adults would visit a post office more than four times
during each five-week programme period, giving the channel a potential
audience of nearly 29m.
Mr Howard Bickley, media markets manager at the Post Office, said the
programmes would be 'seen in the heart of the high street, close to major
retail outlets, where consumers' impulse to respond to direct response
television advertising can be satisfied immediately'.
