<HEADLINE>
FT  16 AUG 94 / Guatemala right wing sweeps elections
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EDWARD ORLEBAR and REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   GUATEMALA CITY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The party of a former general allegedly linked with human rights abuses won
Guatemala's congressional elections on Sunday, the Supreme Electoral
Tribunal said.
The Guatemalan Republican Front party (FRG) led by Christian fundamentalist
General Efrain Rios Montt, won 32 seats in the 80-member Congress, well
clear of the right-wing Party of National Advancement (PAN) with 24 seats,
tribunal president Mario Guerra said. The Christian Democrat party trailed
with 13 seats and other parties won the remaining 11 seats.
Voters appear to have been swayed by the general's promise to root out
corruption and improve security, while largely ignoring his record during
his 17-month de facto rule in 1982-83. Results will be officially ratified
later this week.
The traditional parties which have dominated Congress in recent years and
have come to be viewed with disdain by much of the electorate suffered
heavily, particularly in Guatemala City, where the PAN and FRG appeared to
have won 85 per cent of the vote.
But the FRG's victory was undermined by an abstention rate of almost 80 per
cent, reflecting the deep-seated scepticism towards Congress, which is
widely considered to be deeply corrupt.
The government must gain congressional approval before the end of September
on a Paris Club debt rescheduling and push through tax reforms to meet
commitments to the International Monetary Fund.
