<HEADLINE>
FT  16 AUG 94 / Hoechst boosted by 'ozone-eating' filter
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PARKES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   FRANKFURT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Shares in the German chemicals group Hoechst were invigorated yesterday by
news that it had developed an 'ozone-eating' filter material with a wide
range of industrial and domestic applications - and sales potential of up to
DM500m (Pounds 207m) a year.
Although the maximum local atmospheric concentration of the irritant ozone
was well below recent alarm levels, the Frankfurt-based company's
announcement alerted dealers, who marked the stock up DM8.50 to DM356.
According to Mr Andreas Schleicher, manager of the Noxon project, Hoechst is
negotiating with around 40 companies interested in applying its ability to
convert air- or water-borne ozone into pure oxygen by 'eating' the extra
oxygen atom in ozone.
Potential partners included manufacturers of filters and air-conditioning
appliances for commercial and domestic use and swimming pool and sewage
equipment makers.
Hoechst claimed its research had shown Noxon could destroy concentrations of
up to 200 grammes a cubic metre - some 1.5m times Germany's recommended
outdoor level of 120 microgrammes.
The Hoechst material offered no health risks in itself and had many
promising applications in protecting people from ozone's harmful effects, Mr
Schleicher said. Ozone can cause headaches and irritate lungs, throat and
eyes. Children and the elderly are often especially sensitive.
Hoechst suggested hospitals, old people's homes and schools as likely buyers
of Noxon filters and air-conditioners, along with car and aircraft
manufacturers.
The company was also working on developing ozone sensors for industrial
applications where it was essential to be alerted to the presence of excess
gas. These included ozone generation plants, and offices fitted with laser
printers or large photocopiers. Under German law, workplace concentrations
may not exceed 200 microgrammes per cubic metre.
According to Mr Schleicher, cyclists were among potential beneficiaries from
projects such as the combination of Noxon with other materials such as
activated charcoal in smog masks.
Heavy ozone contamination was the focus of Germany's latest environmental
controversy when drivers in Hoechst's home state of Hesse were ordered not
to exceed 80kmph during the recent heatwave. Fast driving was blamed for an
unacceptably high concentration of atmospheric ozone in the state.
World stock markets, Page 31
</TEXT>
