<HEADLINE>
FT  16 AUG 94 / Moscow denial on plutonium
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN THORNHILL and REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW, BONN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A quantity of weapons grade plutonium found on a Lufthansa flight to Munich
from Moscow last week threatened yesterday to provoke a serious row between
Germany and Russia. Moscow denied the plutonium was Russian, saying an
inventory of all its sources had discovered no loss or theft. German experts
said analysis could pinpoint the point of manufacture in Russia. According
to Munich police couriers detained arriving from Moscow had been carrying
300-350 grammes of plutonium 239  - a few millionths of a gramme of which
will kill - in a lead-lined steel case. It was the third seizure in four
months of weapons-grade material from the former Soviet bloc. A spokesman
from Chancellor Helmut Kohl's Christian Democratic party, claimed yesterday
there had been 267 cases of smuggling of radioactive material since the
Soviet Union collapsed in 1991.
