<HEADLINE>
FT  16 AUG 94 / Companies House to cut charges after EU court ruling
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL CASSELL and ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Companies House is to reduce by half the fees it charges for registering
British companies and for the annual submission of returns to avoid a legal
battle following a recent judgment in the European Court of Justice.
The decision, which will take effect on October 1, is expected to wipe out
the annual contribution made by Companies House - the official repository
for corporate financial information in England, Wales and Scotland - to the
Department of Trade and Industry, which last year stood at Pounds 17m.
Nearly 1m limited liability companies are registered with Companies House,
and last year 115,000 new companies were incorporated for the first time.
The move to cut the charges was taken by the DTI - for which Companies House
operates as an executive agency. It follows a European Court ruling,
involving an Italian company, which interpreted a 1969 Brussels directive to
mean that fees for registering a company must be restricted to
administration costs involved.
Search fees and fines levied on companies for filing their returns after the
due dates will not be affected by the changes. The halving in Companies
House fees - Pounds 50 for incorporation and Pounds 32 for filing annual
returns - coincides with a review of its activities by consultants appointed
by Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary.
Stoy Hayward, the accountancy firm, came up with a list of options for
privatisation last year and is submitting a follow-up study to examine
proposals in more detail by the autumn. It is set to begin canvassing public
views over the next few weeks.
Mr Heseltine is keen to contract out most Companies House services, although
he has indicated that responsibility for the registrar's functions and
ownership of the register will remain with the DTI.
The option under Mr Heseltine's partial privatisation plans which seems most
likely to be favoured involves paying private sector contractors a
management fee akin to the way Companies House now operates, with an annual
target for reduction in costs. Officials have also been considering paying
contractors on the basis of net running costs, in proportion to the workload
handled each year.
The reduction in income brought about by halving fees in the wake of the
European Court ruling was anticipated in the run-up to commissioning the
privatisation studies and is considered unlikely to scupper Mr Heseltine's
plans.
The department said that the fees charged by Companies House have never been
tested legally but the DTI had decided not to challenge the European Court
ruling to avoid the possibility of a protracted legal action.
A DTI spokeswoman claimed that fees charged by Companies House were among
the lowest in Europe.
</TEXT>
