<PROFILE>_AN-EHODDAEKFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940815
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  15 AUG 94 / World Bond Markets: Australian sector braced for rate rise -
International
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TRACY CORRIGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Australian government bond market is braced for a rise in interest rates
 -but then, it has been for the last four months, at least. However,
analysts argue that economic forces are now overwhelming any political
pressure to delay raising rates.
So far, the Australian authorities have been able to fend off pressure to
raise rates because the Australian economy has been relatively slow to pull
out of recession.
'The Reserve Bank of Australia has made it clear that it agrees with the
need to increase interest rates,' said Mr Michael Gallagher, director of
research at IDEA, the market analysis specialist, 'but has been concerned
about relatively modest growth in business investment.' In addition, high
unemployment and a depressed property market have helped fend off rate
increases.
However, economic growth has now accelerated: in fact, at an estimated 4.5
per cent in 1994, it has overtaken the US.
The latest employment data showed a jump of 90,000 jobs in July, compared
with an average increase of 17,000 a month over the last six months, and a
drop in the unemployment rate to 9 1/2 per cent from 10 per cent.
'We expect a 50 basis point rate hike towards the end of September,' says Mr
Paul Donovan, bond analyst at UBS. 'The Reserve Bank is not independent, and
politically there have been mixed pressures. It will probably come in
reaction to a US hike.'
Because the Australian dollar is closely tied to the US dollar, the
Australian bond market tends to track the US treasuries market. However,
despite a series of interest rate rises by the US authorities, the
Australian government bond market has substantially underperformed the US
market.
The yield differential between the two markets has widened from 80 basis
points at the beginning of April to its current level of more than 200 basis
points.
The Australian market has already discounted a series of rate increases.
Overnight cash rates, set by the authorities, are currently 4 3/4 per cent
while six-month bill rates have risen to 6.2 per cent.
So why is the market so bearish? The answer appears to be that inflationary
fears have taken hold, and the country's poor record on inflation has
undermined confidence in the bond market.
Certainly, with inflation at 1.7 per cent and 10-year bond yields at 9.5 per
cent, the market appears to offer attractively high real yields  - among the
highest of the developed markets.
Only Sweden and Canada offer higher real yields, but they both have high
debt to GDP ratios of more than 67 per cent, compared with only 33 per cent
for Australia, according to data compiled by Swiss Bank Corporation.
The high real yields for long-dated bonds in Australia suggest that the
market is expecting inflation to rise sharply.
Indeed, factors such as the recovery in the housing market and increases in
raw material prices could soon boost inflation, according to some analysts,
while the strength of the Australian dollar, supported by strong commodity
prices, could fuel imports.
However, according to analysts at SBC, wages remain the key to inflation and
'there are few signs of any significant inflation pressures in the economy.
The main concern is the legitimacy of the productivity offsets agreed
between unions and businesses to support wage increases (which are)
generally well above underlying inflation.'
For bond investors, most analysts continue to advise caution, in spite of
attractive real yields relative to other markets.
'Australia looks like a bear market and that is not going to change, but
there is some room to outperform other markets,' says Mr Donovan. 'A rate
hike could be supportive.'
Australian bonds are largely held by domestic investors, but because of the
relatively small size of the market, marginal foreign interest can have a
strong impact on prices.
One potential source of funds is Japan, where the weakened yen has led
Japanese investors to look again at the dollar bloc.
However, with the Australian market virtually insisting on a rate rise and
10-year bond yields apparently heading towards double-digit levels, most
investors are likely to hold off a while longer.
One danger is that they will instead choose the New Zealand market, which
has performed well until recent political worries.
According to some analysts, international investors may favour New Zealand
because of its highly independent central bank and the fact that it is an
improving credit, even though 10-year yields, at 8.33 per cent, are
substantially lower than in Australia.
The outlook for the New Zealand market largely depends on whether the
political situation stabilises after the weekend's Selwyn by-election.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>AUZ  Australia.
</CN>
<XX>
