<HEADLINE>
FT  15 AUG 94 / World Bond Markets: Tokyo
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMIKO TERAZONO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Uncertainty in European bond markets and profit-taking by domestic
institutions ahead of the September book closing are expected to weigh on
Japanese government bonds this week.
The higher yen supported bond prices last week on hopes of dampening
prospects of an economic recovery, but such expectations were dashed by
government comments that the economy was gradually pulling out of a slump.
Overall activity may be subdued as many investors are on their Obon holidays
until mid-week. But traders say more banks are shifting their Japanese
government bond portfolios into euroyen straight bond issues.
The moves come as the year's fall in government bond prices has left many
financial institutions with unrealised losses. A Tokyo Stock Exchange
disclosure rule requires listed companies to release unrealised losses on
listed securities portfolios if the figure is equal to or more than 30 per
cent of pre-tax or net profits.
Institutions reluctant to reveal their loss-making positions are switching
into unlisted euroyen straight bonds from government bonds. 'There is a big
switch going on as the supply and demand situation for various classes of
bonds are changing,' says Mr Marshall Gittler, bond analyst at Merrill Lynch
in Tokyo. He says the trend is raising yields in government bonds.
</TEXT>
