<HEADLINE>
FT  15 AUG 94 / World Bond Markets: Frankfurt
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PARKES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Swedish Riksbank's justification of its surprise rates rise with a claim
that it had spotted four inflationary factors prompted a swift review in
Germany. A weakening currency, cited by the Swedes, is not a problem in the
federal republic.
Nor is the speedy global recovery causing concern. Dearer imports have
slowed the fall in German consumer prices, but other factors, such as
shrunken disposable incomes, are keeping inflation under control.
On the other hand, the Riksbank's identification of rising capacity
utilisation in industry rang some bells. As Mr Adolf Rosenstock, economist
at the Industrial Bank of Japan in Frankfurt, noted, this indicator is may
soon over-step its long-term average of 83 per cent.
With this and the turnround in unemployment in mind, he says the Bundesbank
will have to stay on guard. The IG Metall engineering union has already
started making ominous noises about the need for a clear improvement in real
pay.
While Mr Rosenstock marked last Thursday in his diary as the day Europe's
latest spell of monetary easing came to an end, there were still voices
suggesting the Bundesbank has further to go.
Optimists believe the central council will signal its attitude with a return
to variable rate repos at its first post-holiday meeting this Thursday.
</TEXT>
