<HEADLINE>
FT  15 AUG 94 / World Bond Markets: New York
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Encouraging statistics showing that the consumer price index rose by only
0.3 per cent last month eased inflationary fears in the US at the end of
last week, giving bonds an unexpected shot in the arm.
The benchmark 30-year Treasury bond shot up by nearly  3/4 points, sending
the yield down from 7.65 per cent to 7.49 per cent.
Nevertheless, the market remains convinced that an increase in interest
rates is almost inevitable when the Federal Open Market Committee meets
tomorrow.
The reason is that, whatever the consumer price index may say, other
economic data continue to point to inflationary pressures further back in
the supply chain.
Many analysts believe that the Federal Reserve will feel compelled to choke
these pressures off before they feed through into rising prices.
How big the increase will be is another matter. Some analysts seem to think
that 25 basis points will be enough: but paradoxically, a 50 basis point
rise might prove better for bonds, at least at the long end of the market.
Normally, higher interest rates cause bond prices to fall, but in this
instance anything less than a 50 basis point increase might be seen as
insufficient to ensure that inflation had been stifled, posing the threat of
even higher interest rates to come.
</TEXT>
