<HEADLINE>
FT  15 AUG 94 / Tory health plans under attack over talks with US group
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS and ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government's health plans yesterday came under renewed attack after Mr
Tom Sackville, the health minister, said he had held discussions with a US
healthcare group on the provision of services to the National Health
Service.
Labour accused the government of attempting to sell off the NHS to companies
'seeking to escape (US president) Bill Clinton's efforts at cost-cutting'.
Conservative backbenchers also expressed deep unease at the unpopular
decisions which the government may be forced to take by rising health costs.
Mr Sackville said he had held discussions in June with Salick Healthcare,
which was 'one of a number of American companies who are trying to gain a
foothold in the UK'.
However, he insisted that he had told the company, which specialises in
diagnostic and therapeutic services for patients suffering from cancer and
kidney failure, that his department was 'neutral' in any decisions taken by
NHS trusts or fund-holding general practitioners to buy services from
external sources. He said he merely encouraged the health service to
co-operate with the private sector.
The Department of Health denied any health service hospitals had been put on
sale. It said: 'The NHS is not for sale, and neither are any NHS hospitals.'
US healthcare companies are active in the UK, with the Boston-based
Healthcare International recently opening a 260-bed private hospital in
Clydebank, Scotland, aimed mainly at overseas patients. But they have not
bought existing NHS hospitals.
Mr David Blunkett, Labour's health spokesman, said the US companies were
'seeking to soak the British taxpayer with the aid and approval of
government ministers'. He added: 'We must have become a soft touch for easy
profits in health care if the Americans are seeking to escape Bill Clinton's
efforts at cost-cutting and increased efficiency.'
A senior member of the Tory backbench 1922 committee said the debate
underlined the problem of rising healthcare costs. 'No one seriously wants a
US-style healthcare system. But if the government can't afford to pay, it
will increasingly be forced to take up other options, some of which may be
very unpopular.'
Sir Teddy Taylor, Tory MP for Southend East, said: 'This will send shivers
down the spine of those who feel the NHS is moving towards a capitalist
system. The US involvement creates a special horror because of the
persistent stories of American healthcare excluded from those of limited
income.'
Care volunteers 'ignored', Page 6
</TEXT>
<XX>
