<HEADLINE>
FT  15 AUG 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
It is some indication of the credulousness of the human race that a man
should be selected as the subject of a half hour programme because he does
not believe in the supernatural. Richard Dawkins, follower of Darwin and
author of 'The Selfish Gene' and 'The Blind Watchmaker", is interviewed by
Sheena McDonald in The Vision Thing (8.00 C4). It is widely agreed that
religious beliefs should be respected and never attacked or ridiculed, but
Dawkins is not only an atheist, he also regards religion as downright
dangerous; hardly a surprising attitude when you consider the results of
religious fervour from Palestine to Pakistan, from Christianity's
Inquisition to Islam's fatwah on Salman Rushdie. It sounds as though Frank
Stubbs is becoming remarkably politically correct in the last episode of the
present series (9.00 ITV). He sets up a campaign to save a young Chinese
girl from deportation and, when she is threatened by racists, turns them
against the Home Office official. Panorama investigates the way in which
people are now obliged to resort to private landlords (9.30 BBC1).
</TEXT>
