<HEADLINE>
FT  15 AUG 94 / Working Life: Dentist in the house - Health
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MOTOKO RICH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Going to the dentist is probably on most people's list of least favourite
things to do. The thought of giving up as much as a day's work to commute to
a dental surgery, on top of hated drillings and fluoride treatments, means
many employees may never make it to get their teeth cleaned by a dentist.
The cumulative cost of their eventual visits to the dentist can be very
large.
To encourage employees to keep up their dental health, about 30 large
companies in the UK, including Glaxo, Marks and Spencer, ICI and National
Power - as well as the Bank of England - now provide dental services for
their staff.
These services range from contracts with National Health Service dentists to
comprehensive in-house programmes with independent dental surgeons.
According to Leslie Kaye, dental surgeon for Glaxo Research and Development
and Glaxo Holdings, the company's in-house dental service saves up to 2,000
days of work because employees do not need to take time off to travel to see
a dentist.
At Glaxo R &amp; D's site in Greenford, Middlesex, Kaye, a hygienist and two
dental surgery assistants regularly see 1,600 patients from the company's
staff. They also provide services to 800 more employees from Glaxo's site in
Ware. About 60 per cent of Glaxo R &amp; D and Glaxo Holdings' staff use the
on-site dental surgery.
Kaye is a NHS dentist, although Glaxo is considering moving the dental
practice into the private sector. About 75 per cent of dentists working in
industry are still in the NHS, though Jo Freeman, senior dental surgeon at
Glaxo Pharmaceuticals in Stockley Park and president elect of the
Association of Industrial Dental Surgeons, says more companies are moving in
the direction of independent dental services.
At Glaxo R &amp; D and Holdings, the government pays for 20 per cent of any
dental service while each patient pays for 80 per cent. However, because the
company pays for its dental staff's salary, Kaye says he can spend more time
with each patient as he is not working for a fee. While the average
non-industry NHS dentist books about 40 appointments a day, Kaye only puts
about ten to 15 patients into the dental chair each day.
Glaxo subsidises the more expensive services, such as crowns and bridgework.
which an increasing number of NHS dentists do not provide. The dental
surgery also checks employees for oral cancer as part of the company's
general health screening programme.
Kaye says that setting up an in-house service requires a relatively small
capital investment for ultimately high savings for the company. He estimated
that most of the necessary equipment for a dental surgery could be purchased
for about Pounds 25,000.
It is not just the large companies which can benefit from dental services.
He says dental programmes become cost effective once a company has 700
employees or more. Smaller companies in office blocks can combine to hire
one dentist.
A company interested in the upkeep of its staff's teeth should hire a
dentist who is willing to set up the service, rather than trying to
establish the service before bringing in a dentist to run it.
'Any time an opening comes up in industry, there is a very high demand for
the job,' says Kaye. 'Many dentists want to leave general practice. They
want to get out of the rat race.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Glaxo Research and Development.
    Glaxo Holdings.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
