<HEADLINE>
FT  15 AUG 94 / Sport: Kick off kicks out summer
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURA THOMPSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
At the end of last week I opened a newspaper for a lazy, crickety read about
the possible recall of Mike Gatting for the Oval test. I found instead a
frantic, footballian debate about the resignation of Billy Bonds from the
manager's job at West Ham. I am not exaggerating when I say that this
depressed me a good deal. Surely, I found myself thinking, August is summer
and summer is cricket and, with all due respect, Billy Bonds is not somebody
that I want inside my head for at least another month.
Last weekend I had sat like a lotus-eater amid the desultory crowd at the
Headingley test match, steeped in the syrup of sloth. A bare week later I
find that the world has changed completely. It has become alert and brisk
and energetic, as if already trying to stave off the chill of winter.
Cricket, of course, is still with us. But its time has gone: really it is
already dead, a mere flicker of white ghosts upon a mirage of green,
trampled down into the memory by the great size 12 boots of football. It is
impossible, somehow, to give cricket the slow attention it deserves when one
is being harried and worried about whether or not Alan Shearer has
hepatitis. I know that darkness has begun to encroach upon summer evenings
and that the still air of July has been blown through with autumn. But do we
have to succumb so early? Must we relinquish so suddenly those gorgeous
images of sunlit grass to those of mud and grime?
I feel this strongly because I have, to paraphrase T S Eliot, measured up my
life in sporting events. At the merest mention of the boat race, for
example, I sense a fresh spring wind upon my face; the sight of those hefty
blazered boys tripping down to the river causes my year to flower. By the
day of the FA Cup final I am primed for summer, which is heralded by Derby
Day at Epsom and which seems to ripen, to burgeon with riches, as the
sporting occasions accumulate within it: Ascot, Wimbledon, Henley, Goodwood,
the Greyhound Derby, the test matches.
An ineffable melancholy attends the end of each of these events. Unlike the
football season, which seems to go on forever and then, having stopped at
last, seems to start again almost immediately, the summer sporting occasions
are essentially finite, fleeting things. Because of this, however bored I
might be by them when they're actually happening, I can never bear to lose
them.
I find myself enjoying those twinkly resume films, in which tennis players
hug line judges to the tune of 'Always look on the bright side of life.' I
watch the final trophy presentations with pleading eyes, as if silently
begging the protagonists not to leave me. After the World Cup Final I sat in
front of the rolling list of credits, staring stupefied and almost tearful
at the names of sound men and floor managers.
Ten years ago I would not have behaved in this way. Then I was of an age to
take delight in the reassuring recurrence of sporting events, without
feeling the need to slow down the inexorable cycle that they rode. Now,
however, I feel that, although the occasions are rolling around the same as
ever, I am growing a year older as they do so.
Because of this, a moment like Martina Navratilova's last exit from the
Centre Court takes on great poignancy. When she first appeared at Wimbledon,
I was a child; I have grown up in the years that she played there; now she
has gone, and she has taken my past with her.
Identifying thus strongly with the landmarks of the sporting year, it is
hardly surprising that I feel a pang when the football season starts, as if
a door has been closed upon the summer. With the World Cup barely over, this
season seems especially premature. Get that manly cabal of commentators, who
only last month were sweltering and pontificating their way across America,
off my screen. Give me Tony Lewis and Richie Benaud and the sense that the
year is eternally suspended at its still centre.
The worst thing of all is that I know how easily I shall give way, despite
having so far ignored every thing to do with football, even the signing of
bete blond Jurgen Klinsmann. I know that, like those women who stuff their
Christmas turkeys on the day they return from their summer holidays, I too
shall soon start wishing my year away, setting my face against the fading
sun and immersing myself in the twilight comfort of the Classified Football
Results.
The start of the football season implies an imminent relapse into a
different, winter life. After the sun and glamour-drenched theatricals of
summer, it feels like returning to Nescafe after a few brief weeks of Douwe
Egberts. It also feels inevitable. Football is reliably disappointing and
disappointingly reliable but, because of this, it has a substance, a proper
place in everyday life. I believe in it far more strongly than in those
precious summer events which, like many lovely things, live more in the
memory than in the reality.
Perhaps that is the true reason why I dread the start of the football
season: not because it says that the year is coming to an end, but because
it says that the year - by which I mean the real year, the tough cold
repetitive ordinary year - is about to begin.
</TEXT>
