<HEADLINE>
FT  15 AUG 94 / Working Life: Paretsky fires a blank - Reading Matter
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Sara Paretsky is attempting to create a new genre of detective fiction: the
politically correct murder story.
Paretsky burst into the world of detective writing in the early 1980s with a
striking innovation - VI Warshawski - a hardened, likable woman private
detective tramping around Chicago.
In the early novels, Bitter Medicine, Deadlock and Burn Marks, Warshawski
was charming and credible, the plots were dense with detail and red
herrings.
But with her latest book, Tunnel Vision, something awful has happened to VI
Warshawski: she has become more important than the murder she is
investigating.
The point of the latest, very long book is the detective herself, not the
plot of murder, money laundering and political corruption she uncovers.
And that is not the only problem: the heroine's character has become
increasingly unappealing. VI Warshawski now seems to be shaped by what
appear to be Paretsky's political preferences rather than her reflections
upon Chicago life.
The book reeks of political correctness: there are women's building
co-operatives, exploited Romanian construction workers, a token black
boyfriend, child abuse, and homelessness.
Warshawski's behaviour is increasingly preposterous and many of the exploits
in which she displays her miraculous powers are incidental to the plot - a
thinly-built tale of a senator's company making illegal grain sales to Iraq
and laundering the proceeds through a local bank which some friends have
just bought.
Paretsky's decline is all the more striking when compared with the brooding
power of White Butterfly, the latest book from Walter Mosely, the rising
star of US detective fiction.
Tunnel Vision's self indulgence is capped with a sickly surprise birthday
party at which Warshawski is surrounded by droves of adoring friends, many
of them saved and reformed by their contact with the saintly detective.
The only absentee is the long-suffering black boyfriend Conrad. Earlier in
the story he gives Warshawski the elbow. On this showing readers should
probably follow suit.
Charles Leadbeater
</TEXT>
