<DATE>940815
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  15 AUG 94 / Working Life: Customer service pitched just right - Eating
Out
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
One of the reasons why I decided not to go into the wine and restaurant
trade, after doing much of the early training, was a reaction to keeping up
the pretence that the customer is always right. The customer is quite often
wrong, as you will know if you have been a wine waiter and seen perfectly
decent wine turned back in order to show off, or had coffee rejected because
it is not decaffeinated, then returned to be congratulated for the speed of
the switch while bringing exactly the same coffee back.
There are two answers. One is to avoid restaurants whenever possible, except
on holiday. The other is never complain: if something is wrong, say nothing,
but don't go back. Above all, beware of familiarity. If the waiters start
fawning to you, it is time to move on. For the mark of a really good
restaurant is that you can drop in anonymously, even though it might be wise
to book.
Chez Gerard in London's Chancery Lane is a test case. It is one of the few
decent places conveniently situated between the City and Westminster and
takes in the lawyers on its doorstep. It has a reputation for being slightly
aloof; several women have told me that it does not take kindly to female
bookings. On the other hand, it has some of the best frites in London.
Last Thursday - the day after the night of the London rain - was a testing
time. Wet umbrellas and all, the place was packed even by the standards of
Chez Gerard.
The initial service was understandably slower than usual. Courteous French
efficiency, however, soon resumed. Fizzy water was quickly and quietly
exchanged for still. We learned in passing from a waiter - and without
interruption to the service - that the only place in London to go for
Belgian frites (which are the best of the lot) is a restaurant in Chalk
Farm.
The first courses - pate and cold duck - were excellent, and decently small.
Yet not everything was perfect. My colleague ordered steak tartare. This
really is a test case for a restaurant, but if the restaurant puts it on, it
must expect to be tested.
When it arrived, it looked a bit large to me, but my colleague demurred and
gamely set about it. She did not get through to the end but, having the
right instincts, would not have dreamed of complaining. She said merely to
me - and even then only when asked - that it was 'a bit chewy'.
A senior waiter noticed. He came to see if anything was wrong. The word
'chewy' was whispered. The waiter took away the steak tartare, returned to
say that he had had it examined in the kitchen, found that it was not up the
restaurant's best standards, and apologised. My colleague was offered
another course or a deduction from the bill. All that was done with the
minimum of fuss and without sycophancy.
We concluded that on a difficult day Chez Gerard had passed all the tests
without even knowing it was being tested. As London restaurants go, it is
not particularly expensive. You can eat well with wine for two for just
under Pounds 50, and if you take the fixed price menu the cost is lower
still.
Chez Gerard, 119 Chancery Lane, London WC2. (071) 405 0290
Malcolm Rutherford
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
