<HEADLINE>
FT  15 AUG 94 / Engineers' chief to quit IoD in protest
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL CASSELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The controversy in the business community over the acceptable level of
government support for UK industry has been re-ignited with the protest
resignation from the Institute of Directors of Mr Noel Davies, president of
the Engineering Employers' Federation, Michael Cassell writes.
Mr Davies, who is also chief executive of VSEL, the submarine and
shipbuilding group, has told the IoD that he is leaving the organisation
because of its support for demands by Mr Michael Portillo to cut the level
of state aid given to industry. Mr Portillo, now the employment secretary,
made the demands when he was chief secretary to the Treasury.
The Confederation of British Industry has said it fully supports Mr Michael
Heseltine, trade and industry secretary, who is resisting calls for
reductions in his budget.
In a letter to Mr Tim Melville-Ross, who has just taken over as IoD director
general, Mr Davies says he will not renew his personal membership because of
remarks made recently by Mr Melville-Ross in which he endorsed Mr Portillo's
call for a fundamental review of public expenditure across all government
departments.
The IoD chief questioned the effectiveness of some state funding for
industry and said all government spending had to be scrutinised if taxes
were to be lowered.
Mr Davies says the IoD's views are contrary to those of others 'who I
believe know and understand the problems of industry better'.
The IoD said last night that the organisation had received critical letters
from only three of its 32,500 members.
Mr Melville-Ross said he was sorry Mr Davies had indicated his intention not
to renew his membership.
He added: 'I hope he will reconsider when he has had a chance to read my
explanation of the context in which I expressed the IoD's support for a full
review of public expenditure so that we can ultimately reach a point when
both the borrowing requirement and the burden of taxation can be reduced in
the interest of all businesses.'
</TEXT>
