<HEADLINE>
FT  15 AUG 94 / Knapp accuses Railtrack of bullying and misleading
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Jimmy Knapp, leader of the RMT transport union, yesterday accused
Railtrack of bullying and refusal to compromise as a further 48-hour strike
by signal workers started last night.
He also accused Railtrack of misleading the public with its Pounds 100,000
newspaper advertising campaign yesterday.
The company said its offer would mean an average of 7.2 per cent on earnings
between April and October, with a final agreement giving increases of up to
10 per cent on earnings.
Mr Knapp said average earnings under Railtrack's proposals would go up by
less than 4 per cent, 'but signalling grades have to give up a tremendous
amount for even this'.
He added: 'And if Railtrack are so confident about the fairness of the
package, why do they continue to refuse to tell the union how much they will
save?
'Personal contracts mean a worsening of conditions as Railtrack's
restructuring package shows. It is also an invitation for Railtrack to
continue their campaign of harassment and bullying.'
The union said the company's arguments in the advertisements had been
'dismissed by a sceptical public', and welcomed a MORI poll in the Mail on
Sunday showing that 56 per cent of the public believed signalling grades
should get more money, while only 20 per cent backed Railtrack.
A spokesman for the company rejected Mr Knapp's claims, saying it was the
union which was inflexible for insisting on an interim pay deal before it
would discuss restructuring.
Mr Frank Dobson, shadow transport secretary, said: 'The government has been
stringing out the strike because it thought it would be to their political
advantage, and people would turn against the signal workers.
'The MORI poll shows this is not happening. The government should cut its
losses and let the dispute be settled.'
The Department of Transport said Dr Brian Mawhinney, the transport
secretary, had changed his holiday plans and was now spending two weeks
somewhere in the UK to keep in touch with developments.
