<HEADLINE>
FT  15 AUG 94 / Tunnel link data to be issued soon
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Department of Transport said yesterday that it would announce details of
the intermediate stations which will be needed on the Pounds 2.7bn Channel
tunnel rail link in the next two weeks.
Details of the stations for the 68-mile route, which will link London's St
Pancras station with the Channel tunnel, were originally expected by the end
of May.
A series of delays has prevented the department from providing the four
bidders for the project - which is regarded as a pilot scheme for the
government's private-finance initiative for infrastructure projects - with
the detailed specifications they need to prepare bids.
Once these are available the formal tendering process is set to take six
months. The government expects to introduce a bill authorising the project
in the next parliamentary session and aims to pass the legislation in 1996.
The rail link could then open in 2002.
The department yesterday defended itself against accusations that it was
taking too long to provide information to the four bidders. 'They are
complex tender documents and they've got to be absolutely right. Although
one or two people in the private sector may be thinking it's taking a long
time, these things do take a long time.'
Four consortia are bidding: Eurorail, including GEC, Trafalgar House and
BICC; London &amp; Continental; Hochtief of Germany; and a fourth including the
construction companies John Mowlem and Taylor Woodrow.
The three losers will each be paid compensation worth a third of the costs
of their bid, up to a maximum of Pounds 1.5m each. They had to inform the
government of their interest in April, and have assembled teams of expensive
professional advisers, who as yet have nothing to do.
</TEXT>
