<HEADLINE>
FT  15 AUG 94 / Housing land prices up 35.3%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MOTOKO RICH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The price of land for residential building in England rose 35.3 per cent in
the year to June, says a survey of land values by Savills, the residential
research company.
Land prices have jumped 23 per cent in the first half of this year, with the
biggest increases concentrated in the south-east, south-west, East Anglia
and, most prominently, in the east Midlands.
Since June 1992 land values in England have risen 48 per cent, exceeding the
most optimistic Savills forecast. At the start of this year researchers
predicted prices would rise 20 per cent during the year.
This unexpected performance may be attributed to a recovery from previous
price falls. Residential land has been hit much harder by a decline in
property values than the housing market generally. From June 1989 to 1992
the price of edge-of-town and serviced land, as well as level sites with
outline planning permission for medium-density dwellings, fell an average of
52 per cent.
The Savills index of residential building land is 582.3. It is estimated
that prices will have to increase by a further 40 per cent for the index to
regain its 1989 peak of 817.2.
</TEXT>
