<HEADLINE>
FT  15 AUG 94 / Councils 'ignore care volunteers'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Local authorities have ignored help from volunteer groups when implementing
community care, a report says today.
Community Service Volunteers, which co-ordinates voluntary groups, said that
only 28 per cent of councils in England and Wales had plans to use help from
the voluntary sector in community care for this year, while only one-third
had staff with specific responsibility for dealing with offers of voluntary
help.
It suggested that the government's controversial care in the community
programme could work better and more cheaply if councils took advantage of
help offered without charge by individuals. Although 93 per cent of councils
said they planned to work with voluntary organisations, far fewer actually
made use of help from volunteers.
Of a sample of 60 authorities contacted by the organisation, 45 per cent
said they made no use of volunteers.
Ms Elisabeth Hoodless, executive director of the group, said that councils
should be barred under the Citizen's Charter from ignoring offers of help.
She said: 'Volunteers have proved they are a vital force in lengthening and
strengthening our public services, but the majority of authorities still
deny them a chance to serve.'
CSV said its survey of plans showed that where volunteers were already
involved, councils were making increased use of them, mostly with a range of
client groups.
Volunteers: Partners in Care. CSV, 237 Pentonville Road, London N1 9NJ.
Pounds 5
</TEXT>
