<HEADLINE>
FT  15 AUG 94 / Greens show black flag at Monza grand prix: Cancellation of
Italian motor race to spare trees has upset the locals
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW HILL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Frantic shuttle diplomacy, riot warnings, conspiracy theories, resignation
threats and emergency legislation: a normal holiday weekend in Italy.
The subject of all this frenzied activity was not last week's turmoil on the
bond, currency and stock markets, but Friday's decision by Fia, the world
motor sport authority, to cancel the 65th Italian Grand Prix.
The decision was supposed to end uncertainty caused by a row between
tree-hugging environmentalists and road-hogging Formula One drivers over
modifications to the venerable Monza circuit, set in an ancient royal park
near Milan. Instead it has set off a new wave of controversy.
Environmental groups are protesting against proposals to fell more than 100
trees and extend the gravel-filled safety lane at a fast right-hand bend of
the track for the September 11 race. Drivers called for the improvement
after the accident which killed Ayrton Senna at the San Marino grand prix
earlier this year.
Over several weeks, local and national authorities dithered about whether
trees or turbos should have precedence, until Friday when Fia decided it had
had enough.
Environmentalists - standing guard over the trees lest fanatical motor sport
'tifosi' decided to take an axe to them - seemed strangely subdued by the
decision. 'From the beginning we have always said that we are not against
this year's grand prix,' said Mr Matteo Barrattieri of the Worldwide Fund
for Nature on Friday, speaking from the other side of the fence erected by
the Monza authorities to mark out the felling area. 'We're against the fact
that instead of reducing the speed of the cars they want to damage the
park.'
While the greens are reluctant to declare victory, advocates of the grand
prix are certainly not going to concede defeat. Mr Aldo Moltifiori, mayor of
Monza, has resigned in protest, alleging, among other things, a conspiracy
between Ferrari and Fiat (which controls the sports car maker) to take the
grand prix to the company-owned track at Mugello in Tuscany. Other regional
politicians, all members of the populist Northern League, have also
threatened to step down.
On Saturday, a delegation headed by Mr Gianni Letta, chief of staff to Mr
Silvio Berlusconi, the Italian prime minister, flew to Cannes to try to
persuade Fia to change its mind. Meanwhile, Mr Umberto Bossi, head of the
Northern League, emerged from his all-night summit with Mr Berlusconi
promising that an emergency decree would save the grand prix.
According to Mr Moltifiori, direct and indirect earnings from the grand prix
amount to L70bn (Pounds 29m) a year, with 100 jobs depending directly on the
race, and a further 1,400 temporary employees helping on race day itself.
He blames Mr Letta for ending Monza's hopes by asking Fia to agree to the
installation of a new chicane before the bend, an alternative which the
sport's authorities had already rejected. 'A government which can't manage
to stage a grand prix ought to give up and go home,' Mr Moltifiori said on
Friday. Fia has so far stood by its decision.
One of Mr Moltifiori's last acts as mayor was to warn the local prefect of
police that he could no longer be responsible for the actions of an angry
populace. This holiday weekend, however, Monza was completely closed and
almost deserted. A policeman on a bicycle, who was stopping cars from
entering the historic centre on Friday, said he was disappointed: 'After
all, Monza is known worldwide for its grand prix, not for its trees.' Only
the gatekeeper at the Monza circuit expressed anything like an inflammatory
reaction to the decision. 'There's only one thing for it now,' he said with
a shrug. 'Revolution.'
</TEXT>
